Problem:
Part of the graph of $f(x) = ax^3 + bx^2 + cx + d$ is shown. What is $b$?

[asy]
unitsize(1.5 cm);

real func(real x) {
  return((x + 1)*(x - 1)*(x - 2));
}

draw(graph(func,-1.1,1.5));
draw((-1.5,0)--(1.5,0),Arrows(6));
draw((0,-1)--(0,2.5),Arrows(6));

label("$x$", (1.5,0), E);
label("$f(x)$", (0,2.5), N);

dot("$(-1,0)$", (-1,0), SE, fontsize(10));
dot("$(1,0)$", (1,0), SW, fontsize(10));
dot("$(0,2)$", (0,2), NE, fontsize(10));
[/asy]

answer:
Using long division,
\[
\begin{array}{c|cc cc}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{4x^2} & -2x & +3/2  \\
\cline{2-5}
2x+5 & 8x^3 & +16x^2&-7x&+4  \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{-8x^3} & -20x^2& \\ 
\cline{2-3}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{0} & -4x^2& -7x\\ 
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & +4x^2& +10x\\ 
\cline{3-4}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 0& +3x & +4\\ 
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & -3x & -15/2\\ 
\cline{4-5}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & & & -7/2\\ 
\end{array}
\]So the quotient is $\boxed{4x^2 -2x + \frac{3}{2}} $.

